  Relevance to inference_dalek

  The skills references are exactly the kind of content that should feed inference_dalek's prompts. Compare:

  ┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┬─────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │                inference_dalek v26 prompt                │           Equivalent skill reference            │
  ├──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ "Proof Generation Rules" (loop invariants, proof blocks) │ techniques.md (18 techniques)                   │
  ├──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ "Verus Syntax Rules"                                     │ common-issues.md (error fixes)                  │
  ├──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ Generic domain knowledge                                 │ SKILL.md (type invariants, where to put lemmas) │
  ├──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ "IMPORTANT CONSTRAINTS" (in repair prompt)               │ quality-bar.md (checklist)                      │
  ├──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ Available Lemmas section                                 │ lemma-reference.md (search priority, placement) │
  └──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┴─────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

  Key differences in quality:

  1. techniques.md is better organized than v26's rules — it has 18 numbered techniques with clear "when to use" guidance. The v26 prompt mixes loop
  invariants with proof fn rules and Seq updates into one blob.
  2. common-issues.md addresses real failure modes — "Extract array elements before entering proof blocks", "nested proof blocks not supported", "SMT
   rlimit fixes". The v26 repair prompt has none of this.
  3. workflow.md has the incremental approach — "moving assume(false) technique" which is proven to work for complex proofs. inference_dalek's repair
   loop doesn't use this pattern.
  4. patterns.md has worked examples from the actual codebase — not synthetic pseudocode like v26's f(x, n) example.

  What inference_dalek should steal from these files

  1. Replace the generic "Proof Generation Rules" section with a filtered subset of techniques.md relevant to the proof type (induction → techniques
  #7, #14, #15; loop invariant → techniques #8, #15, #18).
  2. Use common-issues.md in the repair prompt — when the repair loop sees a specific error type, include only the relevant fix from
  common-issues.md. E.g., AssertFail → include "scope lemma calls with assert-by"; rlimit → include "opaque specs + targeted reveal".
  3. Use lemma-reference.md search priority for filtering available lemmas — "same file → common_lemmas/ → domain folders" is a better relevance
  heuristic than name-matching.
  4. Use quality-bar.md as the success criteria for the repair loop — "all admits replaced, verification passes, minimal assertions" instead of just
  "errors == 0".
  5. The axiom_references.md could help inference_dalek understand which admit() calls are intentional axioms (don't try to prove them) vs provable
  gaps (do try). Currently inference_dalek treats all admit() the same.